metadata.name: Mountain Peak #19
A Forgotten Landscape #1
What on Earth? #37
metadata.description:
'What on Earth?' expands upon the history of my last piece 'Terra'. This is a speculative scifi projection taking inspiration from the IPCC reports on climate change. This piece is an imagination of the possibility of the multiverse. 

It is a generative art piece that uses six base maps for the different types of earth. The two other layers are procedurally generated and overlayed on each other resulting in 6x4x5 possible combinations. However there is always a chance of getting multiple planetary accessories which increase the number of unique possible variations. Each of the pieces also come with their unique version of narrative embedded in the piece itself. 

Instruction:
Hover in the top right corner of the canvas to reveal a button to access the story and the settings. This is an interactive piece - click and drag to turn/play with your earth. 

Photosensitivity Warning: Viewer discretion is advised before you turn on 'Acid' inside settings. It involves flashing imagery and glitching effects.

metadata.name: The Arcade State #73
metadata.description:
"The Arcade State is a strange place.
You can only walk in four directions. Which will it be? 
As you make your way across the landscape, you will discover lush grasslands, grim structures, and colorful grounds. And if you get lucky, you might unearth artifacts of other times, hidden deep inside the system."
   - The Architect -


I am an artist and a scientist fueled by challenges. I'm most creative when I can't work under perfect conditions and I have to improvise to find a solution.
For The Arcade State, I constrained myself to only using four angles along the circle (45, 90, 135, and 180 degrees) while still producing interesting images with depth and variety.


Keys:
Press 'e' to export the image in HD  (1600x2000)
Press 'h' to export the image in UHD (4800x6000) - this will take a few seconds

metadata.name: “The blunt dagger.” -Randoms Performances. #2
metadata.description:
“The most painful stab wounds are those that corrode from the shadows, imperceptible, they slip through the body.”

This is a collab with Gregorio Nash (@gregorionash).

Technical Data :
Five movements that mix infinitely, each combination makes for a unique performance. It also has an "Old Vintage" shader that gives an old and worn feeling. The movements were created from a sensoperceptive experimentation through the body kinesphere, decanting a saying of the body understanding the sensations from an active role.

Variations :
- 5 performances.
- Infinite palette color possibilities
- Shader "Old Vintage".

thanks to Julian Puppo (@jpupper), for helping us with the construction of the code and the shaders.
thanks to Javier Meseguer (jmpep) for shader “old vintage”.

metadata.name: A long starry night #13
metadata.description:
This generative landscape is animated, some animations are very slow and take around 2 hours to loop.
This experience is best viewed fullscreen (click 'open' and go fullscreen) between FHD and QHD resolutions.

Press 'K' on the keyboard to go in the exploration mode. There you can drag the view with touch or mouse and orbit around stellar cluster.
Press 'K' again to embark on a travel following a celestial object.
Press 'SPACE' keyboard to take a screenshot (PNG) at current resolution.

metadata.name: Interactive Seeds #16
metadata.description:
This interactive piece brings back some good old childhood memory.

Click anywhere on the canvas to blow the seeds away.
The closer to the seeds you click, the stronger the wind force applied to them.

Want to play again?
Just press 'r' to pull the seeds back.

Have fun!

Made with p5.js.


[ Controls - live mode only]

Mouse
- press: blow seeds away from the cursor
- release: stop blowing and freeze the frame

Keys
- r: rewind to pull back the seeds
- 1: minimal resolution 1000x1000 (Default)
- 2: medium resolution 2000x2000
- 4: high resolution 4000x4000
- s: save the image as PNG


[ Special Thanks ]

- Daniel Shiffman for the free eBook "The Nature of Code"
- Warped Perception for the YouTube video "Dandelions Blown - In 4K Slow Motion"


[ Features ]
1. Aspect Ratio: 1x1 / 2x3 / 3x2 / 3x4 / 4x3
2. Dandelions: 1 / 2 / 3 / 4
3. Palette: Sky and Hills / Grayscale / I'm feeling lucky / Just the Dandelions
4. Frame: None / Random / Rounded
5. Background: Single Color / Solid Shapes
6. Seed: Y / I
